# Mood & Munch вҖ” Implementation Plan

A context-aware food recommendation app that combines five real-time signals (time, weather, activity, mood, hunger) with Gemini AI to deliver personalized, nutritionally-grounded meal suggestions from multiple global cuisines.

## Architecture Overview

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph Frontend["React + Vite (Port 5173)"]
        A[Login Page] --> B[Dashboard]
        B --> C[Context Input Panel]
        C --> D[Mood Chips]
        C --> E[Hunger Chips]
        B --> F[Results Panel]
        F --> G[Meal Cards]
        F --> H[Avoid List]
        F --> I[Hydration Tip]
        F --> J[Next Meal Hint]
    end
    
    subgraph Backend["Node.js + Express (Port 3001)"]
        K[Auth Middleware] --> L[/api/recommend]
        L --> M[Weather Service]
        L --> N[Fit Service]
        L --> O[Gemini Service]
        L --> P[Session Service]
    end
    
    subgraph ML["Python Flask (Port 5000)"]
        Q[/api/preferences] --> R[Preference Engine]
    end
    
    subgraph Google["Google Services"]
        S[Firebase Auth]
        T[Firestore]
        U[Weather API]
        V[Google Fit API]
        W[Gemini API]
    end
    
    B -->|ID Token| K
    M -->|lat/lng| U
    N -->|OAuth Token| V
    O -->|Context JSON| W
    P -->|Read/Write| T
    A -->|Google Sign-In| S
    R -->|Read History| T
```

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **API Keys Needed**: You will need to provide the following API keys/credentials before the app can connect to live services. Until then, the app uses **mock data** so you can see the full UI and flow working:
> - Google Maps Platform API key (with Weather API enabled)
> - Google Cloud OAuth 2.0 Client ID (for Firebase Auth + Google Fit)
> - Firebase project config (apiKey, authDomain, projectId, etc.)
> - Firebase Admin SDK service account JSON
> - Gemini API key

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Monorepo Structure**: The project will be organized as a monorepo with three services (`client/`, `server/`, `ml-service/`) in the workspace root. Each has its own `package.json` / `requirements.txt`. Is this structure acceptable?

## Open Questions

> [!NOTE]
> **Google Fit OAuth**: Google Fit requires the user to grant OAuth consent for `fitness.activity.read` scope. The current plan uses a demo/mock mode for activity data by default, with a toggle to connect real Google Fit data. This avoids blocking the demo on OAuth consent screen setup.

> [!NOTE]
> **Python ML Service**: The Flask ML microservice learns cuisine preferences over time from feedback. For the initial build, it will use a simple weighted-average model. Is a more sophisticated model (collaborative filtering, etc.) needed for v1?

